\section{Problem}{
 "data must contain only non-negative values (raw counts required)"

\strong{Cause:} Your data contains negative values, which shouldn't exist in raw count data.

\strong{Solutions:}
\itemize{
  \item Check if your data has already been log-transformed or normalized
  \item Verify you're using raw counts, not FPKM, TPM, or RPKM values
  \item Look for data processing errors (e.g., subtracting background incorrectly)
  \item If you have a few negative values, replace them: \code{data[data < 0] <- 0}
}

\strong{Example Fix:}
\preformatted{
  # Check data before analysis
  summary(data)  # Look for Min < 0
  table(data < 0)  # Count negative values

  # Replace rare negative values
  data <- pmax(data, 0)  # Replace negatives with 0
}

 "data contains non-finite values (Inf, -Inf, NaN)"

\strong{Cause:} Your count matrix has infinite or NaN values, often from:
\itemize{
  \item Division by zero in prior preprocessing
  \item Log-transformation of zero values
  \item Data import errors or file corruption
}

\strong{Solutions:}
\itemize{
  \item Investigate source of non-finite values
  \item Use \code{remove_problematic_genes = TRUE} to auto-remove problematic genes
  \item Or manually fix: \code{data[!is.finite(data)] <- 0}
  \item Check if data needs re-importing from source files
}

\strong{Example Fix:}
\preformatted{
  # Identify problems
  inf_genes <- which(apply(data, 1, function(x) any(!is.finite(x))))
  inf_samples <- which(apply(data, 2, function(x) any(!is.finite(x))))

  # Option 1: Auto-remove (if using DESeq2 functions)
  results <- find_degs_deseq2(
    data = data,
    sample = sample_metadata,
    remove_problematic_genes = TRUE  # This removes affected genes
  )

  # Option 2: Manual fix
  data[!is.finite(data)] <- 0
}

 "Sample(s) missing from metadata" or row name mismatch

\strong{Cause:} Sample IDs in your count matrix don't match rownames in metadata.

\strong{Solutions:}
\itemize{
  \item Ensure column names in data match rownames in sample metadata
  \item Check for trailing spaces, different case, or special characters
  \item Reorder metadata to match data column order
}

\strong{Example Fix:}
\preformatted{
  # Check alignment
  colnames(data)           # Column names in data
  rownames(sample_meta)    # Row names in metadata

  # Reorder metadata to match data
  sample_meta_aligned <- sample_meta[colnames(data), ]

  # Or fix names to match
  rownames(sample_meta) <- colnames(data)

  # Check for invisible issues
  all.equal(colnames(data), rownames(sample_meta))
}

 "Formula variables not found in sample metadata"

\strong{Cause:} Your design formula references column names that don't exist in metadata.

\strong{Solutions:}
\itemize{
  \item Check spelling and case sensitivity of variable names
  \item Verify variable exists: \code{colnames(sample_metadata)}
  \item Use valid column names in formula
}

\strong{Example Fix:}
\preformatted{
  # Check available variables
  colnames(sample_meta)
  # [1] "group" "batch" "replicate"

  # Correct formula
  formula = ~ group + batch  # Use available columns
  # Wrong: formula = ~ condition + batch  # "condition" doesn't exist!

  # Create missing variable if needed
  sample_meta$condition <- sample_meta$group  # Create from similar variable
}

 "At least 3 replicates per condition (6+ recommended)"

\strong{Cause:} Statistical methods require sufficient replication for reliable estimates.

\strong{Solutions:}
\itemize{
  \item Generate more biological replicates if possible
  \item Consider pooling samples carefully if only a few samples available
  \item Use more lenient thresholds (e.g., padj < 0.1 instead of 0.05)
  \item Acknowledge limited statistical power in your analysis notes
}

\strong{Example Check:}
\preformatted{
  # Check replicate counts
  table(sample_meta$group)

  # If insufficient:
  # - Add more samples (preferred)
  # - Use less stringent significance thresholds
  # - Report results cautiously
}

 Plotting functions not displaying or showing warnings

\strong{Cause:} Usually related to missing data, invalid grouping variables, or ggplot2 issues.

\strong{Solutions:}
\itemize{
  \item Check that \code{color.by} and \code{shape.by} reference valid columns
  \item Ensure sample metadata is properly aligned with data
  \item Check for extreme outliers that distort plot scales
  \item Verify ggplot2 and ggprism packages are installed
}

\strong{Example Debug:}
\preformatted{
  # Verify column exists
  "group" %in% colnames(sample_meta)

  # Check data consistency
  nrow(sample_meta) == ncol(data)

  # Verify no missing values in grouping columns
  sum(is.na(sample_meta$group)) == 0

  # Simplify plot call temporarily
  pca_results <- pca_analysis(
    data = data,
    sample = sample_meta,
    plot.type = "none"  # Disable plots to isolate issue
  )
}

 DESeq2 analysis fails with model fitting errors

\strong{Cause:} Issues with experimental design, rank-deficiency, or data quality.

\strong{Solutions:}
\itemize{
  \item Check for confounding variables in your design
  \item Verify all formula variables are factors or continuous
  \item Remove genes with all zero counts: \code{data <- data[rowSums(data) > 0, ]}
  \item Check for batch effects that should be in the model
  \item Simplify model: start with \code{~ group} and add complexity gradually
}

\strong{Example Fix:}
\preformatted{
  # Filter low-abundance genes first
  data_filtered <- data[rowSums(data) >= 10, ]  # Keep genes with ≥10 total counts

  # Start with simple model
  results <- find_degs_deseq2(
    data = data_filtered,
    sample = sample_meta,
    formula = ~ group  # Simplest design
  )

  # Then add complexity if needed
  results <- find_degs_deseq2(
    data = data_filtered,
    sample = sample_meta,
    formula = ~ batch + group  # Add batch correction
  )
}

 "No significant results found"

\strong{Cause:} Your data may not show significant differences, or thresholds are too stringent.

\strong{Solutions:}
\itemize{
  \item Relax thresholds: try \code{padj = 0.1} instead of \code{0.05}
  \item Lower fold-change threshold: try \code{log2FoldChange = 0.5} instead of \code{1.0}
  \item Verify your experimental design is correct
  \item Check data quality: sufficient replicates, low technical noise
  \item Consider whether true biological effect exists in your data
}

\strong{Example Exploration:}
\preformatted{
  # Explore distribution of fold changes
  all_results <- find_degs_deseq2(
    data = data,
    sample = sample_meta,
    log2FoldChange = 0,  # No FC threshold
    padj = 1.0           # No p-value threshold
  )

  # Visualize what you have
  hist(all_results$log2FoldChange, breaks = 50)
  plot(all_results$log2FoldChange, -log10(all_results$padj))
}
}

\section{Best Practices}{


\enumerate{
  \item \strong{Validate Input Data}
    \itemize{
      \item Check dimensions: \code{dim(data)}, \code{dim(sample_meta)}
      \item Verify sample alignment: \code{colnames(data) == rownames(sample_meta)}
      \item Check data types: \code{str(data)}, \code{str(sample_meta)}
    }
  \item \strong{Start Simple}
    \itemize{
      \item Begin with basic parameters and simple models
      \item Add complexity gradually (batch correction, interactions, etc.)
      \item Verify each step works before proceeding
    }
  \item \strong{Quality Control}
    \itemize{
      \item Remove low-abundance features (e.g., genes with few counts)
      \item Check for and handle outliers appropriately
      \item Examine batch effects and confounders
    }
  \item \strong{Interpretation}
    \itemize{
      \item Don't rely solely on p-values; consider effect sizes
      \item Multiple testing creates many false positives; use FDR correction
      \item Validate findings with independent data or biological knowledge
    }
  \item \strong{Documentation}
    \itemize{
      \item Document your analysis workflow and parameter choices
      \item Save session info: \code{sessionInfo()}
      \item Report which bioRtools version was used
    }
}
}

